
📘 Sorting in Spring Data JPA

1️⃣ Concept
Sorting = retrieving data in ordered form based on a field.
👉 Two main ways:
Using Sort class (dynamic, flexible)
Using method naming (OrderBy) (static, fixed)

2️⃣ Approach
✔️ Approach 1: Using Sort Class (Dynamic)
Sorting decided at runtime
Can pass field name + direction dynamically

✔️ Approach 2: Using Query Method (OrderBy)
Sorting fixed in method name
No runtime flexibility

3️⃣ Code

🔹 A. Using Sort Class
Repository (no extra method needed)
List<ProductEntity> findAll(Sort sort);


Service / Controller usage
import org.springframework.data.domain.Sort;

@GetMapping("/sorted")
public List<ProductEntity> getSortedProducts() {
    return productRepository.findAll(Sort.by("price").ascending());
}


Descending
return productRepository.findAll(Sort.by("price").descending());


Multiple fields
return productRepository.findAll(
    Sort.by("price").descending()
        .and(Sort.by("quantity").ascending())
);


🔹 B. Using Query Method (OrderBy)
Repository
List<ProductEntity> findByOrderByPriceAsc();
List<ProductEntity> findByOrderByPriceDesc();


Controller
@GetMapping("/sort-asc")
public List<ProductEntity> getAsc() {
    return productRepository.findByOrderByPriceAsc();
}

@GetMapping("/sort-desc")
public List<ProductEntity> getDesc() {
    return productRepository.findByOrderByPriceDesc();
}


4️⃣ Key Points
🔑 Sort Class
Dynamic sorting ✅
Can sort by multiple fields ✅
Cleaner for APIs with query params
Uses:
Sort.by("field").ascending()


🔑 Query Method (OrderBy)
Static sorting ❌ (fixed at compile time)
Method name becomes long
Case-sensitive keywords:
OrderBy + FieldName + Asc/Desc


5️⃣ Learnings / Interview Insights
⭐ When to use what?
Use Case
Best Choice
Dynamic sorting (API param)
Sort class
